We prioritize the use of open source models because we believe it is in line with the ethos of Bittensor. Of course, we could get better performance if we asked miners to connect to Google's translation API, but we believe in using open-source technologies to create a more robust and decentralized network.

As we know, open-source solutions are quite limited, while Don mentioned, fast translations are not always necessary, and our time limit is 10 seconds, which is fine for many applications. However, we could improve the inference time in the following ways:

-Dynamically adjust the waiting time based on the length of the input data. For example: miners could have less than 2 seconds to respond.

-Add streaming so that miners can send their progress while doing translations. This would require adding a whole new synapse and many additional complications, but we certainly have the skills to do it.

-Reducing wait times. This could prevent us from recommending Aya unless we lower the maximum number of tokens. We could go so far that miners would be forced to use the M2M version of cTranslate2, but this would be at the expense of translation quality.

As for auto-detect, we have already had this system in code for a long time, our Discord Bot and Twitter Bot, among others, use it, while we do not yet have it applied to the translator on the site. We are working to introduce it there as well in the near future.

Thank you very much for your feedback, we will work on improving these aspects so as not to affect the quality of our translations.

Hi, sn12 compute horde owner here. I'm working with an NGO that is supporting international law enforcement understand where and how much human trafficking happens, in order to better direct the efforts of interpol and such. That particular NGO is now trying to significantly enhance their reporting capabilities by adding analysis of news written in Spanish, but their classification and analysis models are only capable of analysing English, so a need for translation of the news from Spanish to English has arised. Quality and cost-efficiency of those translations is somewhat important, so before we go all in on the first solution for this problem that they came up with, I'd like to consult this briefly with sn2 miners to make sure it's all going in the right direction

the use an aggregator to get 2000-3000 articles/day from just one source and they have 4 or 5 sources like that. When they run one article (700-800 words typically, but translators have limitations so they break it down to sentences and translate each sentence separately) on a laptop, it takes 2-3 minutes to translate a single article. We think they would benefit from running their workloads on compute horde (sn12) by offloading the translation to GPU-equipped hardware provided by the subnet miners.

they found two models that help them translate:
1. https://huggingface.co/Helsinki-NLP/opus-mt-es-en
2. https://huggingface.co/mrm8488/mbart-large-finetuned-opus-es-en-translation

From what they say, the second model has higher quality than the first one.

Now, have they missed some model with even higher quality that you know of? Or maybe you know of some other way of doing this that would be better than their current approach?

The other thing is that these articles are not "any" Spanish text but it's somewhat specific, so they think maybe one day they could fine-tune an existing model to teach it how to perform these translations better.

Finally they do have a problem with evaluating their results, they can use google translate or ChatGPT to try to translate and compare it with the results ran on the opensource models. These are expensive to run, too. Their experience is limited, but the cause is noble - I had a chat with them and found some disturbing facts that motivated me to help them do what they want to do a bit faster. I thought I was making good money on backend software development, but then I learned how much a pimp can earn per month by successfully exploiting a trafficked woman in the UK by making her work in a brothel. Believe it or not, there is a number, but knowing it does not make your life easier, so I won't say it out loud here.

Let's break down step by step!

- if we are going to implement this feature to the subnet, we should make dataset public.
- validators will load public dataset(which are the pairs of input and output), and send synapse with input data only.
- Miners were supposed to use models to generate response. 
   BUT they don't use their model, just take the same workflow with validator.
   ACCESS the dataset and find input data, then return the output.
- They are cheating but will get 100% score.

Hi @ here: 

We will be shortly upgrading the testnet chain with Dynamic TAO. 
In order to prepare testnet subnet for this change read this document: https://docs.bittensor.com/dynamic-tao

It is essential that your upgrade your Bittensor version to work with the new chain (we will inform you when that has been done) or else some of the common commands your miners/validators use i.e. like `subtensor.metagraph` to retrieve the latest network state ***will fail***. Please read the above document explaining how you can change to the correct branch and avoid this situation.

Aside from the upgrade to the SDK and CLI, you should experience very little change in the actual consensus of your network. Why? because the normal TAO staked on your validators will still be counted in each mechanism. Within the next month or more your subnet token will begin to have more effect on the dynamics of Yuma Consensus. We will be releasing more information on how this work technically later.

We will do our best to explain more about this upgrade and what you need to know at todays Novelty Search. Please come at the usual time of Thursday, January 9, 2025 3:00:00 PM today.

Best
